body:
Visa seems to be great for the long term (5+ years) as society continues to transition to being cashless, MA &amp; Visa are simply in the business of processing transactions so unlike Square they do not face risk from credit card debt. The only knock on Visa is that the stock is priced very high relative to their revenue/income growth rate. It is priced high because it is seen as a very safe investment with a bright future. They run the risk that any sort of societal change that hurts their business model means a high probability they won't reach their peak stock price ever again since it's priced in so high relatively to how much money the company actually brings in. For ex: Who knows if there's technology that will be invented that could disrupt Visa and Mastercard's business. For all we know Apple could announce some sort of tech that undermines Visa/Mastercard's business model and Visa's stock price in that case is very likely to not recover if they can't regain market share. That is why Warren Buffet pushes you to know a business inside and out before investing, so you truly know the economic significance/dominance a company has for it to continue to grow. I know Visa is gaining market share over MC in Asia, while MC is dominating Europe from what I've heard.

&amp;#x200B;

As for Facebook, Facebook is trading at a discounted price relative to how much revenue/income growth they have. If you take Facebook's average 20% growth annually and projected the next 10 years they should be trading around $260ish. The reason Facebook is trading lower is because of the fear of government intervention that will break them up. The thing with Facebook though is that it is so intertwined with our other accounts like spotify, and that they dominate social media there isn't any reason to believe the company will die (they own Instagram and WhatsApp if you didn't know).

&amp;#x200B;

Visa is probably the safer investment, and is a better long term play. However, Facebook imo is worth the risk given the discount their stock price trades at. We have at least already seen the EU and US embarrass themselves with the Zuckerberg hearings showing their ignorance to tech. That doesn't mean if the market has a correction/recession that Visa is susceptible to never reaching its peak stock price again. It took Microsoft until 2017 to recover from the 2000 .com bubble. Context matters when evaluating stock prices!

&amp;#x200B;

Edit: In terms of opportunity cost you will find out faster whether or not Facebook is a good investment or not. Visa you run the risk of steady increases hoping the price never crashes (at least if you buy Visa at its current price), if you buy Visa after its price crashes and average down you could be fine, assuming the price crash/dip is a true overreaction (fortunately, there are a lot of overreactions in the stock market thanks to bots nowadays).
